<p>The combination of high electricity costs, substantial federal incentives, and Alaska's surprisingly adequate solar resource makes renewable energy systems financially attractive for many homeowners. During Alaska's long summer days, solar panels can produce exceptional amounts of electricity, while modern cold-climate heat pumps and high-efficiency HVAC systems can dramatically reduce heating costs during the state's harsh winters. The key to success in Alaska lies in proper system sizing, equipment selection designed for extreme climates, and taking advantage of available incentives.</p>

